<h2> Michigan Imputation Server on Docker </h2>

<h3>Summary</h3>
This tutorial sets up the Michigan Imputation Server on <a target="_blank" href="https://www.docker.com/">Docker</a>. 
To impute against the <a target="_blank" href="http://www.haplotype-reference-consortium.org">HRC</a> or TOPMed reference panel, please use the official instance of the
<a target="_blank" href="https://imputationserver.sph.umich.edu">Michigan Imputation Server</a>.

<h3>Requirements</h3>
Docker must be installed on your local computer. Please checkout the 
<a target="_blank"  href="https://docs.docker.com/engine/installation/linux/ubuntu/">step by step guide</a> to install the latest version.

<h4>Check Docker Version</h4>
<pre>
docker --version
Docker version 17.12.0-ce
</pre>

<b>Important:</b> A local sudo user (not root) is required to run the image.

<hr>

<h3>Michigan Imputation Server: Quick Start</h3>

After the successful installation of Docker, all you need to do is:

<h4>Setup</h4>
<pre>docker run -d -p 8080:80 genepi/imputationserver</pre>

After ~ 1 minute your Imputation Server instance is ready and you are able to access it on http://localhost:8080 and impute against HapMap2.

<h4>Connect</h4>
<pre>http://localhost:8080
<b>Credentials</b>: admin / admin1978
</pre>

<hr>

<h3>Download test data</h3>
A sample file (chromosome 1) including ~23k SNPs (simulated HapMap300 chip) can be found  <a target="_blank" href="https://imputationserver.sph.umich.edu/static/downloads/hapmap300.chr1.recode.vcf.gz">here</a>.
<hr>

<h3>Michigan Imputation Server: Install 1000G Phase 3</h3>

To keep your jobs, results and installed reference panels between sessions, you need to mount a folder from your host to the container:

<pre>
docker run -d -p 8080:80  -v /home/user/imputationserver-data/:/data/ genepi/imputationserver
</pre>

<h4>Add new panel</h4>
After logging in, you have to open the Admin-Panel:

<img src="/static/images/help/admin-panel.png" class="img-rounded" width="900px">

Click on the Applications tab to see all installed applications.


